\begin_layout Title
Yet Another Riemann Hypothesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Linas Vepstas <linas@linas.org>
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
12 October 2004
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This short note presents a peculiar generalization of the Riemann hypothesis,
 as the action of the permutation group on the elements of continued fractions.
 The problem is difficult to attack through traditional analytic techniques,
 and thus this note focuses on providing a numerical survey.
 These results indicate a broad class of previously undiscussed functions
 may obey the Riemann hypothesis in general, and even share the non-trivial
 zeros in particular.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Riemann zeta can be expressed as an integral in the following form
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Edw74"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-s\int_{0}^{1}h(x)x^{s-1}dx\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \[
h(x)=\frac{1}{x}-\left\lfloor \frac{1}{x}\right\rfloor \]

\end_inset

is sometimes called the Gauss map.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor y\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 is the largest integer less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The Gauss map lops of a digit in the continued fraction expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 If one writes the continued fraction expansion
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Khin35"

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $0<x\le1$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
x=[a_{1},a_{2},a_{3},\cdots]=\frac{1}{a_{1}+\frac{1}{a_{2}+\frac{1}{a_{3}+\ldots}}}\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)=[a_{2},a_{3},\cdots]$
\end_inset

.
 It is a (reverse) shift operator on the continued fraction expansion.
 The study of continued fractions is interesting because of their proximity
 to various problems of fractals and dynamical systems, including ties to
 Farey fractions, the modular group via the Cantor set, and the Minkowski
 question mark function.
 More immediately, the transfer (Ruelle-Frobenius-Perron) operator of the
 Gauss map is the Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsing operator, which has a number of interesti
ng properties of its own.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this note, we observe that the Gauss map can also be thought of as one
 particular element of the permutation group acting on an infinite dimensional
 representation of the real numbers.
 Thus, we are lead to contemplate other elements of the permutation group.
 Specifically, consider the permutation operator 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S_{p,q}:[a_{1},\cdots,a_{p},\cdots,a_{q},\cdots]\mapsto[a_{1},\cdots,a_{q},\cdots,a_{p},\cdots]\label{eq:Permutation Elts}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which exchanges the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

'th and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

'th digits of the continued fraction expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{p,q}$
\end_inset

 maps the unit interval onto the unit interval, and is discontinuous at
 a countably infinite number of points.
 The generalized Riemann hypothesis that we choose to explore concerns the
 zeros of the integral
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta_{p,q}(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-s\int_{0}^{1}S_{p,q}(x)x^{s-1}dx\label{eq:zeta-permute}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This integral can be evaluated, but only with considerable difficulty.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{p,q}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is a piece-wise combination of unimodular Mobius functions, that is, a
 piece-wise collection of 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}\]

\end_inset

with integer values of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ad-bc=\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 This structure follows from the general theory of continued fractions
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Khin35"

\end_inset

.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Graphs"

\end_inset

 below provides a set of graphs visualizing 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{p,q}(x)$
\end_inset

, showing their piece-wise nature.
 The functions are clearly 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fractal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or self-similar; a general discusion of the self-similarity is given in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ve-M04"

\end_inset

.
 Because of the piece-wise structure, the integral can be evaluated analytically.
 The result is a messy set of nested sums that don't seem to provide any
 particular insight; the evaluation is given in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Sums-and-Integrals"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easier, at first, to explore this integral numerically.
 Treating the integral as a very simple Newtonian integration sum with equally
 spaced abscissas, one gets:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta_{N;p,q}(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-\frac{s}{N}\;\sum_{n=0}^{N-1}S_{p,q}\left(\frac{2n+1}{2N}\right)\;\left(\frac{2n+1}{2N}\right)^{s-1}\label{eq:zeta-pq-sum}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This summation converges very slowly and very noisly as 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 but a numerical evaluation for large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 can give some basic insight.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Continued Fractions; Permutation Groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that continued fractions provide a representation of the real numbers
 in the infinite Cartesian product space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}^{\omega}=\mathbb{N\times N\times}...$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}=\mathbb{Z}^{+}$
\end_inset

 is the set of positive integers.
 Note that this implies that each point in this space can be given a unique
 real value using the continued fraction mapping, and that each (non-rational)
 real number appears only once in this space.
 In other words, the continued fraction brackets are an operator that maps
 this space to the real numbers, 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $[\,]:\mathbb{N}^{\omega}\mathbb{\rightarrow R}$
\end_inset

.
 What makes the 
\begin_inset Formula $[\,]$
\end_inset

 operator so interesting is that it is 1-1 and onto, and is thus invertible,
 at least on the irrationals, if we brush aside a little problem with the
 rationals.
 Note that in this mapping, the number 0 is a kind-of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

essential singularity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

, since the continued fraction expansion for 0 is 
\begin_inset Formula $0=[\infty,a_{2},a_{3},...]$
\end_inset

 for arbitrary integers 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, all rationals suffer in this way: a finite continued fraction is
 just one where 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 appears somewhere in the expansion, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $[a_{1},a_{2},...,a_{N}]=[a_{1},a_{2},...,a_{N},\infty,a_{N+2},...]$
\end_inset

.
 We can paper around this difficulty by considering instead 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{M}=\mathbb{N}\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

, defining continued fractions as sequences in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{M}^{\omega}$
\end_inset

, and finally taking the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $[\,]$
\end_inset

 and defining a quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{S}=\mathbb{M}^{\omega}/\ker[\,]$
\end_inset

, so that the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $[\,]:\mathbb{S}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 1-1 and onto in this quotient space.
 In particular, this implies that the inverse map 
\begin_inset Formula $[\,]^{-1}:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

 exists and is well-defined.
 
