\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}\]

\end_inset

it is enough to evaluate the indefinite integral 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}x^{s-1}dx\]

\end_inset

This integral does not have any simple, closed-form solution, but can be
 given in terms of some infinite sums.
 These may be obtained via the Newton series 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(1+x\right)^{s}=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\dbinom{s}{k}x^{k}\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\binom{s}{k}=\frac{\Gamma\left(s+1\right)}{\Gamma\left(k+1\right)\Gamma\left(s-k+1\right)}\]

\end_inset

is the binomial coefficient.
 The indefinite integral may then be evaluated as a sum:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
F\left(s,\alpha;x\right)= & \int\frac{x^{s}}{x+\alpha}dx\\
= & \int\frac{\left(y-\alpha\right)^{s}}{y}dy\\
= & \left(-\alpha\right)^{s}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\binom{s}{k}\left(\frac{-1}{\alpha}\right)^{k}\int y^{k-1}dy\\
= & \left(-\alpha\right)^{s}\left[\ln\left(x+\alpha\right)+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{\left(-1\right)^{k}}{k}\binom{s}{k}\left(1+\frac{x}{\alpha}\right)^{k}\right]\end{align*}

\end_inset

This allows the Mobius integral to be written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}x^{s-1}dx=\frac{a}{c}F\left(s,\frac{d}{c};x\right)+\frac{b}{c}F\left(s-1,\frac{d}{c};x\right)\]

\end_inset

Using that fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $ad-bc=\pm1$
\end_inset

 in general, one may write the above as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}x^{s-1}dx=\frac{\left(-d\right)^{s-1}}{c^{s+1}}\left[\mp\ln\left(x+\frac{d}{c}\right)+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{\left(-1\right)^{k}}{k}\binom{s-1}{k}\left(1+\frac{cx}{d}\right)^{k}\left(\frac{\pm s+kbc}{k-s}\right)\right]\label{eq:mobius sums}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1,2}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, we can give an explicit form:
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_{1,2}\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{a_{2}+\frac{1}{a_{1}+r}}\]

\end_inset

when 
\begin_inset Formula \[
x=\frac{1}{a_{1}+\frac{1}{a_{2}+r}}\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=\left\lfloor 1/x\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}=\left\lfloor x/\left(1-a_{1}x\right)\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 are integers.
 Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and replacing, one gets
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_{1,2}\left(x\right)=\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
a= & 1+a_{1}\left(a_{2}-a_{1}\right)\\
b= & a_{1}-a_{2}\\
c= & \left(a_{2}-a_{1}\right)\left(1+a_{1}a_{2}\right)\\
d= & 1+a_{2}\left(a_{1}-a_{2}\right)\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $ad-bc=1$
\end_inset

.
 This form is valid over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\underline{x},\overline{x}\right)=\left(\frac{a_{2}}{1+a_{1}a_{2}},\frac{1+a_{2}}{1+a_{1}+a_{1}a_{2}}\right)\]

\end_inset

and so one may combine these elements to write 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{0}^{1}S_{1,2}\left(x\right)x^{s-1}dx=\sum_{a_{1}=1}^{\infty}\sum_{a_{2}=1}^{\infty}\int_{\underline{x}}^{\overline{x}}\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}x^{s-1}dx\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The summations are only conditionally convergent; one cannot interchange
 the sum over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 with the sums over 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

; the sums over 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 are logarithmically divergent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately, the nature of Newton series is that they can have considerable
 difficulty converging, as the binomial coefficient gaurentees that terms
 get quite large, and only the alternating sign leads to cancellations.
 By using the expression 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mobius sums"

\end_inset

 for the integral, one can exchange the order of the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2}$
\end_inset

 summations, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 summation.
 Define
\begin_inset Formula \[
\alpha\left(s\right)=\sum_{a_{1}=1}^{\infty}\sum_{a_{2}=1}^{\infty}\left.\frac{\left(-d\right)^{s-1}}{c^{s+1}}\ln\left(x+\frac{d}{c}\right)\right|_{\underline{x}}^{\overline{x}}\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula \[
\beta\left(k,s\right)=\sum_{a_{1}=1}^{\infty}\sum_{a_{2}=1}^{\infty}\left.\frac{\left(-d\right)^{s-1}}{c^{s+1}}\left(1+\frac{cx}{d}\right)^{k}\right|_{\underline{x}}^{\overline{x}}\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula \[
\gamma\left(k,s\right)=\sum_{a_{1}=1}^{\infty}\sum_{a_{2}=1}^{\infty}\left.\frac{\left(-d\right)^{s-1}}{c^{s}}b\left(1+\frac{cx}{d}\right)^{k}\right|_{\underline{x}}^{\overline{x}}\]

\end_inset

 so that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{0}^{1}S_{1,2}\left(x\right)x^{s-1}dx=\alpha\left(s\right)+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{\left(-1\right)^{k}}{k}\binom{s-1}{k}\left(\frac{s\beta\left(k,s\right)+k\gamma\left(k,s\right)}{k-s}\right)\]

\end_inset

The goal of this re-ordering of the summations is to perform the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 summation last, thus keeping the poor convergence of the Newton series
 from disturbing the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2}$
\end_inset

 sums.
\end_layout

